    question:
      'You have read an article about the challenges of moving to a new school. Using the ideas from the passage, write a letter to a friend who is about to change schools, offering advice on how to settle in.\n\nBase your letter on the following passage ideas:\n- Joining clubs and activities helps you meet people with shared interests\n- The first week is the hardest but it gets easier\n- Being yourself is more important than trying to fit in\n- Teachers are usually understanding and supportive during the transition\n- Keeping in touch with old friends while making new ones is important\n\nWrite between 250-350 words. You will receive up to 15 marks for writing and 10 marks for reading.',
    modelAnswer:
      'Dear Sam,\n\nI heard you\'re moving to Westfield Academy next term, and I know you\'re worried — so I wanted to share some advice that I wish someone had given me when I changed schools.\n\nFirst, sign up for something. It doesn\'t matter what — football, debate club, the school play. The point isn\'t the activity itself; it\'s that clubs give you a reason to talk to people. When I joined the science club at my new school, I met three people in the first session who are now my closest friends. You don\'t have to be good at whatever it is. You just have to show up.\n\nI won\'t lie to you: the first week will be difficult. You\'ll eat lunch feeling conspicuous. You\'ll get lost between classrooms. You\'ll miss the shortcuts and in-jokes and comfortable routines of your old school. But here\'s what nobody tells you: by the third week, you\'ll have your own shortcuts, your own routines, and the beginning of your own in-jokes. It happens faster than you think.\n\nThe most important thing I learned is this: don\'t pretend to be someone you\'re not. I made that mistake initially, agreeing with opinions I didn\'t hold, laughing at jokes I didn\'t find funny. It\'s exhausting, and eventually people see through it. The friendships that last are the ones built on honesty. Be yourself — the right people will find you.\n\nAlso, don\'t be afraid to ask teachers for help. Most of them remember what it\'s like to be new, and they\'ll go out of their way to make sure you\'re okay. It doesn\'t make you weak to say, "I\'m finding this hard." It makes you sensible.\n\nFinally, keep texting me. New friends don\'t replace old ones — they add to the collection. I\'ll want to hear everything.\n\nYou\'re going to be fine. Better than fine.\n\nYour friend,\nAlex',
