    question:
      'Re-read the following passage. Select words and phrases that the writer uses to describe the storm, and explain the effects.\n\n"The sky had turned the colour of a bruise — purple-black and swollen with rain that had been building for three days. When it finally broke, it broke with fury. Rain didn\'t fall; it attacked. It came at the windows horizontally, driven by a wind that had lost all pretence of being weather and had become, instead, a kind of madness. The old oak at the end of the garden bent double, its branches scraping the lawn like arthritic fingers. Inside the house, the lights stuttered, died, and returned diminished — as if the electricity itself was frightened."',
    modelAnswer:
      'The writer uses a range of figurative and sensory techniques to present the storm as violent, animate, and psychologically threatening.\n\nThe simile "the colour of a bruise" is immediately effective because it humanises the sky, associating it with physical injury. The adjective "swollen" extends this bodily metaphor, suggesting the sky is wounded and inflamed. The phrase "building for three days" adds a temporal dimension that implies the storm has been deliberately gathering its strength, giving it a sense of intentionality.\n\nThe short sentence "it broke with fury" uses the abstract noun "fury" to attribute human emotion to the storm, while the repetition of "broke" at the start and end of the sentence creates a structural emphasis that mirrors the sudden violence of the downpour. The writer then subverts expectation: "Rain didn\'t fall; it attacked." The semicolon creates a pause that emphasises the contrast between the expected ("fall") and the actual ("attacked"), and the verb "attacked" explicitly frames the storm as an aggressor.\n\nThe personification intensifies with the description of the wind losing "all pretence of being weather" and becoming "a kind of madness." This is a sophisticated technique — by suggesting the wind is performing an identity beyond its natural role, the writer creates a sense of the supernatural. The noun "madness" introduces psychological threat, which is more disturbing than physical danger alone.\n\nThe simile of the oak\'s branches "scraping the lawn like arthritic fingers" combines personification with physical vulnerability. "Arthritic" suggests the tree is old and weakened, creating pathos, while "scraping" is an uncomfortable, harsh verb that evokes an unpleasant sound.\n\nFinally, the personification of electricity being "frightened" is striking because it attributes fear to something inhuman and intangible. If even electricity — a fundamental force — is afraid, the storm must be truly extraordinary. The verbs "stuttered, died, and returned diminished" create a three-part structure that traces the electricity\'s decline, mirroring the human response to overwhelming fear.',
