      "Write a description of a busy market or bazaar.\n\nIn your writing, create a sense of the atmosphere and the people.\n\n[25 marks]",
    modelAnswer:
      "The noise reaches you before the market does.\n\nIt arrives as a hum — indistinct, promising — and by the time you turn the corner it has become a roar, a wall of sound composed of a thousand individual voices all speaking at once, none listening, all entirely sure that what they have to say is the most important thing in the world.\n\nThe first stall sells nothing you recognise. Fruits the size of rugby balls, their skins the violent green of traffic lights, are stacked in precarious pyramids beside baskets of dried fish that stare at the sky with resigned, papery eyes. The stallholder — a woman whose age is impossible to guess, wrapped in fabric so bright it seems to vibrate — watches you with professional interest, decides you are not a buyer, and returns to the important business of arguing with the woman at the next stall about something that happened, apparently, in 1987.\n\nYou move deeper.\n\nThe aisles narrow. Canvas awnings overlap above you, creating a patchwork ceiling that filters the sunlight into something amber and ecclesiastical. Underfoot, the ground is uncertain — cobblestone giving way to packed earth giving way to wooden pallets laid over what might, optimistically, be called drainage. You learn quickly to watch where you step.\n\nA boy, no older than ten, appears at your elbow with a tray of mint tea in glasses so small they look like thimbles. You take one. It is scalding and sweet and tastes, somehow, of the colour green. He vanishes before you can pay, which means you will spend the rest of your visit feeling pleasantly indebted.\n\nAt the centre of the market, the spice stalls form their own republic. Saffron. Turmeric. Cumin. Cinnamon. Cardamom. They sit in open sacks, their colours so saturated they look artificial, like paint samples from a world with a higher resolution than this one. A man with hands stained permanently orange scoops them with a brass measure, and the powder rises in small, fragrant clouds that settle on your clothes and will still be there, faintly, a week from now, when you unpack your suitcase and breathe in and are, for one unguarded moment, somewhere else entirely.",
