    modelAnswer:
      'The letter arrived on a Tuesday, which seemed, in retrospect, significant.\n\nTuesdays were the day Noor\'s mother had always set aside for what she called "life administration" — paying bills, answering correspondence, organising the filing cabinet that lived in the hallway like a squat, disapproving relative. If the letter had arrived on any other day, it might have waited on the mat, been stepped over, been used as a coaster for a mug of tea. But it arrived on a Tuesday, and so Noor\'s mother opened it immediately, standing in the hallway in her reading glasses and dressing gown, and by the time Noor came downstairs for breakfast, everything had changed.\n\n"We\'re going to Lahore," her mother said, without preamble.\n\nNoor poured cereal into a bowl. "When?"\n\n"Next month. Your grandmother is selling the house. She wants us to come and... collect things. Before it goes."\n\nThe house in Lahore was a place Noor had visited twice, both times before the age of seven, both times in summer. What she remembered was heat and mangoes and a courtyard where a cat had bitten her index finger, which she had presented to her grandmother with considerable indignation. She remembered her grandmother laughing — not at the wound, but at the outrage — and bandaging the finger with a competence that suggested this was not the first child the cat had bitten.\n\nShe did not remember the house itself. It existed in her memory as a series of sensory fragments: the smell of cardamom in the kitchen, the cool of marble underfoot, the sound of a ceiling fan clicking on every revolution as if counting something.\n\nThey flew from Heathrow on a morning so grey it felt like London was actively trying to make them leave. Noor slept through the safety demonstration and woke somewhere over Turkey to find her mother reading the letter again, lips moving slightly, as if the words might have changed since the last reading.\n\nThe house, when they reached it, was larger than Noor had expected and sadder than she had prepared for. It had the particular quality of a place where someone had once been very happy and where that happiness had slowly, respectfully, withdrawn. The courtyard was overgrown. The cat was gone. The ceiling fan had been replaced by air conditioning, which hummed efficiently and counted nothing.\n\nHer grandmother met them at the door. She was smaller than Noor remembered — but then, Noor had been smaller too.\n\n"The house knows you\'re here," her grandmother said, which Noor understood was not a metaphor.',
