    question:
      'Read the following poem carefully and write a critical appreciation.\n\nYou should comment on the poem\'s content, structure, and the poet\'s use of language.\n\n"The City Planners" (excerpt)\nby Margaret Atwood\n\nCruising these residential Sunday\nstreets in dry August sunlight:\nwhat offends us is\nthe sanities:\nthe houses in pedantic rows, the planted\nsanitary trees, assert\nlevelness of surface like a survey—\nthe roofs all display\nthe same slant of avoidance to the hot sky,\nand the too-fixed stare of the wide-eyed windows.\n\nNothing moves except the cars\nand the certain certainty of the hot noon.',
    modelAnswer:
      'Atwood\'s "The City Planners" uses the mundane suburban landscape as a vehicle for social criticism, revealing the alienation and artificiality beneath the surface of ordered, middle-class life.\n\nThe poem opens with a scene of apparent normality — "residential Sunday streets" — but immediately undermines it. The surprising claim that what "offends" is not chaos but "sanities" inverts expectations: order itself becomes the problem. The plural noun "sanities" is deliberately unusual (the standard form would be "sanity"), and this grammatical oddity mirrors the poet\'s discomfort with a world that is too regular, too controlled.\n\nAtwood\'s diction is pointedly clinical. The adjective "pedantic" applied to the rows of houses attributes a personality flaw to architecture — these houses are not just neat but fussily, irritatingly precise. "Sanitary" trees — presumably planted at regular intervals — are stripped of natural wildness and reduced to hygienic furnishings. The vocabulary of surveying and measurement ("levelness of surface like a survey") transforms a neighbourhood into a blueprint, suggesting that the planners have prioritised geometry over humanity.\n\nThe personification of the houses — "the same slant of avoidance to the hot sky" and "the too-fixed stare of the wide-eyed windows" — is particularly effective. "Avoidance" suggests the houses are deliberately looking away from something (reality? the sky? each other?), while the "too-fixed stare" of the windows implies a forced, artificial alertness. The prefix "too" is doing significant work: it signals excess, a world that is trying too hard to appear normal.\n\nStructurally, the poem uses enjambment extensively, with lines breaking at unexpected points ("planted / sanitary trees," "display / the same slant"). This creates a reading experience that is itself slightly uncomfortable — the reader, like the speaker, cannot settle into a comfortable rhythm. The form resists the very regularity the poem describes.\n\nThe final couplet — "Nothing moves except the cars / and the certain certainty of the hot noon" — creates an eerie stillness. The tautology "certain certainty" is deliberately excessive, as if the poem is mocking the suburb\'s desperate need for assurance. The heat of "hot noon" adds a sense of pressure and stasis, suggesting that this perfect world is on the verge of cracking.',
