    question:
      'How does the writer present the character of the narrator in the following extract?\n\nYou should consider:\n- what the narrator reveals about themselves\n- how the writer\'s use of language creates an impression of the narrator\n- the narrative perspective and its effects\n\n"I am not, by nature, a person who notices things. I walk through rooms and forget them. I meet people and lose their names in the time it takes to shake their hand. My wife says I could witness a crime and describe the criminal as \'sort of medium.\' She is probably right. But on the morning of November the fourteenth, I noticed everything. The particular angle of the light through the kitchen window. The chip on the third tile above the cooker. The way my daughter held her spoon — not gripping it, but balancing it, like a conductor\'s baton. I noticed these things because I knew, though I had told no one, that it was the last morning I would spend in that house."',
    modelAnswer:
      'The writer creates a narrator who is simultaneously self-deprecating and deeply observant, using the contrast between habitual inattention and sudden hyper-awareness to signal that something significant is about to happen.\n\nThe opening declaration — "I am not, by nature, a person who notices things" — establishes the narrator\'s voice immediately. The qualifying phrase "by nature" suggests a philosophical self-awareness; this is someone who has reflected on their own limitations. The specificity of "I walk through rooms and forget them" is paradoxically detailed for someone who claims to be unobservant, creating an early tension between what the narrator says about themselves and what they demonstrate through their narration.\n\nThe wife\'s reported speech — describing the criminal as "sort of medium" — serves two functions. First, it introduces humour, which makes the narrator likeable and trustworthy. Second, it provides external corroboration of the narrator\'s self-assessment, grounding it in domestic reality. The parenthetical "She is probably right" shows the narrator is humble and emotionally intelligent enough to accept criticism without defensiveness.\n\nThe pivot occurs with the conjunction "But," which signals a shift from habitual to exceptional behaviour. The list of observations — "the particular angle of the light," "the chip on the third tile," "the way my daughter held her spoon" — progresses from the environmental to the personal, each detail more intimate than the last. The simile comparing the spoon to "a conductor\'s baton" is striking: it transforms a mundane breakfast scene into something orchestral, suggesting the narrator is composing a memory.\n\nThe final sentence delivers the emotional payload: "I knew, though I had told no one, that it was the last morning I would spend in that house." The embedded clause "though I had told no one" creates dramatic irony — the reader now shares a secret with the narrator, creating intimacy. The ambiguity of "last morning" is the extract\'s most powerful device: it could mean a house move, a divorce, a terminal diagnosis, or something else entirely. This deliberate withholding compels the reader to continue.',
