    question:
      "Write an article for a school magazine arguing whether the minimum age for social media should be raised to 16.\n\nIn your article, you should:\n- present a clear argument\n- use persuasive techniques\n- consider opposing viewpoints\n\n[25 marks]",
    modelAnswer:
      'SHOULD YOU HAVE TO BE 16 TO POST A SELFIE?\n\nThe proposal to raise the social media age limit to 16 sounds, at first hearing, like the kind of sensible-but-boring policy that adults love and teenagers ignore. But before you scroll past this article — and I know you\'re tempted — consider what it would actually mean.\n\nIt would mean no Instagram until Year 11. No TikTok until you can legally drive a moped. No WhatsApp group chats for organising your social life, sharing homework, or sending those memes that are, let\'s be honest, the only thing getting some of us through double maths.\n\nProponents argue that social media damages young people\'s mental health. And they\'re not wrong. The evidence is substantial: a 2023 study by the Royal College of Psychiatrists found that teenagers who use social media for more than three hours daily are twice as likely to report symptoms of anxiety and depression. The constant comparison, the curated perfection, the algorithmic amplification of content designed to provoke rather than inform — these are genuine harms, and they disproportionately affect younger users whose critical faculties are still developing.\n\nBut here\'s the problem with an age limit: it treats the symptom, not the disease. The platforms themselves are designed to be addictive — infinite scroll, push notifications, like counters that function as social currency. Banning under-16s doesn\'t fix any of this. It just delays their exposure to a system that will manipulate them equally effectively at 16, 17, or 35.\n\nMoreover, enforcement is essentially impossible. The current age limit of 13 is widely ignored — approximately 33% of children aged 8-12 have social media accounts. A higher limit would simply create more liars, not fewer users. And it would push young teenagers towards unregulated platforms and private messaging services where safeguarding is even more difficult.\n\nWhat we actually need is better digital literacy education — taught in schools from primary age — combined with genuine regulation of the platforms themselves. Teach young people to recognise manipulation. Teach them to curate their feeds. Teach them that the number of likes on a photo has the same relationship to their actual value as a human being as a horoscope has to their actual future: none whatsoever.\n\nRaising the age limit feels protective. But real protection means equipping young people with the skills to navigate the digital world — not pretending it doesn\'t exist until they\'re old enough to vote.',
