    id: "caie-lit-drama-01",
    title: "Drama: Analysing a Key Scene",
    examBoard: "caie",
    subject: "literature",
    topic: "Drama Analysis",
    difficulty: 4,
    marks: 25,
    timeMinutes: 40,
    question:
      'How does the playwright create tension and dramatic impact in the following exchange?\n\n[Two characters, SARAH and DAVID, are in a kitchen. It is late at night.]\n\nSARAH: You said you\'d be home by seven.\nDAVID: I said I\'d try.\nSARAH: No. You said you\'d be home by seven.\nDAVID: (pause) Things came up.\nSARAH: Things.\nDAVID: At work. Things at work came up.\nSARAH: It\'s eleven o\'clock, David.\nDAVID: I know what time it is.\nSARAH: Do you?\n\nAnalyse the dramatic techniques used and their effects on the audience.',
    modelAnswer:
      'The playwright creates tension through a masterful use of subtext, repetition, and the controlled withholding of information.\n\nThe exchange operates on two levels: the surface conversation about timekeeping, and the unspoken conflict beneath it — which is clearly about trust, honesty, and the state of the relationship. The audience understands immediately that this is not really about being late; it is about what "being late" represents. This gap between what is said and what is meant creates dramatic tension because the audience must interpret the silences as actively as the words.\n\nRepetition is the scene\'s primary technique. Sarah\'s correction — "No. You said you\'d be home by seven" — repeats David\'s own words back to him, transforming them from a casual statement into evidence. The short sentence "No" functions as a verbal full stop, closing down David\'s attempt to rewrite the conversation. When Sarah later echoes his word "Things" — a single-word sentence — she isolates and exposes its vagueness. The repetition forces the audience to hear how inadequate David\'s explanation is.\n\nThe stage direction "(pause)" is the scene\'s most revealing moment. David\'s silence before "Things came up" tells the audience that he is choosing his words carefully — which implies he has something to hide. In drama, a pause is never neutral; it is a space where the truth almost emerges. The audience fills the pause with their own suspicions, which is more effective than any explicit revelation.\n\nDavid\'s self-correction — from "Things came up" to "Things at work came up" — is a crucial detail. The belated addition of "at work" suggests it was not his first instinct to specify where he was, which subtly undermines his credibility. The playwright forces the audience to notice this correction, creating doubt.\n\nSarah\'s final line — "Do you?" — is devastating in its economy. On the surface, it questions whether David knows the time. But the subtext asks a much larger question: "Do you know what\'s happening to us?" Its brevity and ambiguity leave the scene unresolved, which sustains tension beyond the extract itself. The audience is left uncertain about what David has done, what Sarah suspects, and what will happen next — which is precisely the playwright\'s intention.',
