      'Read the following passage carefully and answer the questions below.\n\n"The village of Ittoqqortoormiit clings to the eastern coast of Greenland like a barnacle on the hull of a ship. Its 450 inhabitants live in brightly painted wooden houses — reds and yellows and blues that seem to argue with the monochrome landscape — and survive by hunting, fishing, and a quiet, unadvertised resilience that outsiders frequently mistake for stubbornness.\n\nFor nine months of the year, the sea freezes solid. Dog sleds replace boats. The sun disappears entirely for two months, and when it returns, people stand outside and watch it as though greeting an old friend who has been abroad too long. The nearest town, Tasiilaq, is 500 kilometres away by helicopter. There is no road.\n\nThe children attend a school with twelve pupils and two teachers. They learn Danish, Greenlandic, and — increasingly — English, which arrives via the internet that arrived via satellite that arrived, improbably, in 2004. The oldest resident, Niels, is 87 and has never left. When asked why, he looks at the questioner with genuine puzzlement, as though the question itself is the strange thing."\n\n(a) According to the passage, what are the three main ways the inhabitants survive? [3]\n(b) Explain in your own words why the return of the sun is significant to the villagers. [3]\n(c) What impression does the writer create of the village school? Support your answer with evidence from the passage. [4]\n(d) How does the writer suggest that Niels finds the idea of leaving incomprehensible? [3]\n(e) Identify and explain the effect of one example of figurative language used in the first paragraph. [2]',
    modelAnswer:
      '(a) The three main ways the inhabitants survive are hunting, fishing, and resilience (or determination/self-sufficiency). [1 mark each]\n\n(b) The sun disappears completely for two months during winter, meaning the villagers endure an extended period of total darkness. Its return therefore represents not just a change in weather but a psychological and emotional renewal — a restoration of normality. The writer\'s simile comparing it to "greeting an old friend who has been abroad too long" suggests the sun\'s return is personal and emotional, not merely practical. The villagers stand outside to watch, which implies a communal, almost ceremonial significance. [3 marks for full explanation in own words]\n\n(c) The writer creates an impression of the school as tiny, isolated, but surprisingly connected to the wider world. The detail of "twelve pupils and two teachers" emphasises its small scale, while the multilingual curriculum (Danish, Greenlandic, English) suggests an outward-looking educational philosophy. The tricolon "the internet that arrived via satellite that arrived, improbably, in 2004" uses the repetition of "arrived" to create a chain that emphasises how many steps were required to connect this remote place to the world. The adverb "improbably" acknowledges the unlikeliness of this connection, adding a note of dry humour. [4 marks: 2 for impression, 2 for supporting evidence]\n\n(d) The writer uses the phrase "genuine puzzlement" to show that Niels does not merely choose to stay — he cannot understand why anyone would want to leave. The clause "as though the question itself is the strange thing" reverses expectations: rather than his staying being unusual, the question about leaving is presented as the oddity. This inversion suggests his attachment to the village is so complete that departure is literally inconceivable to him. [3 marks]\n\n(e) The simile "clings to the eastern coast of Greenland like a barnacle on the hull of a ship" compares the village to a barnacle, which is effective because barnacles are small, tenacious creatures that attach themselves permanently to surfaces. This suggests the village is tiny in relation to the vast landscape, but also stubborn and persistent — it holds on despite inhospitable conditions. The verb "clings" reinforces the idea of precarious but determined survival. [2 marks]',
