    id: "caie-lang-p1-comp-02",
    title: "Comprehension: The Psychology of Queuing",
    examBoard: "caie",
    subject: "language",
    topic: "Comprehension",
    paper: "Paper 1",
    questionNumber: "Q1a",
    difficulty: 3,
    marks: 15,
    timeMinutes: 25,
    question:
      'Read the following passage carefully and answer the questions below.\n\n"Nobody likes waiting, but the British have elevated queuing to an art form — or perhaps a religion. We queue for buses, for coffee, for the privilege of queuing again at a different counter. We queue in the rain without complaint, because complaining about the queue would require acknowledging that the queue is unreasonable, and that would undermine the entire social contract.\n\nPsychologists have discovered something curious: our perception of waiting time has almost nothing to do with the actual duration. A ten-minute wait that feels productive — filling in a form, watching a screen, reading the specials board — passes in what feels like three. A three-minute wait with nothing to do feels like ten. This is why airports installed baggage carousels at the far end of the terminal. Walking for seven minutes and waiting for one minute feels faster than walking for one minute and waiting for seven, even though the total time is identical.\n\nThe most hated queue, universally, is the one that appears to be unfair. We can tolerate length. We can tolerate discomfort. What we cannot tolerate is watching someone who arrived after us being served before us. Supermarkets discovered this in the 1970s and invented the single serpentine queue — one line feeding multiple tills — which is mathematically slower on average but feels fairer, and therefore generates fewer complaints.\n\nThe lesson is clear: we do not experience reality. We experience our interpretation of reality. And our interpretation, it turns out, can be redesigned."\n\n(a) According to the passage, why do the British not complain about queuing? [2]\n(b) Explain in your own words how airports use the psychology of waiting to manage passenger satisfaction. [3]\n(c) Why is the serpentine queue described as a paradox? [3]\n(d) What does the writer mean by "we do not experience reality. We experience our interpretation of reality"? [4]\n(e) How does the writer use humour in the first paragraph to engage the reader? Support your answer with two examples. [3]',
    modelAnswer:
      '(a) The British do not complain because doing so would mean admitting that the queue is unreasonable, which would challenge the unspoken social agreement that queuing is acceptable and necessary. Essentially, complaining would expose the absurdity of the system they willingly participate in. [2 marks]\n\n(b) Airports have positioned baggage collection areas far from the arrivals gate. This means passengers spend most of their time actively walking rather than passively standing still. Although the total time between landing and collecting luggage remains the same, the experience feels shorter because walking gives passengers a sense of purpose and progress. The airport has not reduced the wait — it has simply converted dead time into active time. [3 marks for explanation in own words]\n\n(c) The serpentine queue is paradoxical because it is objectively slower (it takes longer on average) but subjectively better (people prefer it). This is because it eliminates the possibility of someone being served out of turn — every customer is served in the order they arrive. People would rather wait longer in a system they perceive as fair than wait less time in a system where luck determines who is served first. The writer presents this as a revelation about human psychology: fairness matters more to us than efficiency. [3 marks]\n\n(d) The writer means that our experience of the world is not a direct, objective recording of events but a subjective interpretation shaped by psychology, expectations, and context. The same duration of time can feel long or short depending on how it is framed. The same queue can feel fair or unfair depending on its structure. The writer\'s broader point is that businesses and designers can exploit this gap between reality and perception — they don\'t need to change the facts, only how we interpret them. The final sentence ("our interpretation can be redesigned") suggests this is both a useful insight and a slightly unsettling one, since it implies we are more easily manipulated than we like to believe. [4 marks: 2 for basic understanding, 2 for developed interpretation]\n\n(e) The writer uses hyperbole to create humour, describing queuing as something the British have "elevated to an art form — or perhaps a religion." The self-correction from "art form" to "religion" escalates the joke, suggesting queuing is not just a skill but a sacred practice. Second, the observation about queuing "for the privilege of queuing again at a different counter" uses ironic repetition to highlight the absurdity of bureaucratic systems — the reward for waiting is more waiting. Both examples use a dry, self-aware tone that assumes the reader shares the writer\'s amused recognition of British behaviour. [3 marks: identification + explanation of effect]',
