    question:
      "Using the passage material, summarise the advantages and disadvantages of remote working.\n\nPassage points:\n- Remote workers save an average of 72 minutes per day by eliminating commuting\n- Home-based employees report 47% higher productivity on focused tasks\n- Loneliness and isolation are the most commonly reported drawbacks\n- Companies save approximately £8,000 per year per remote employee on office costs\n- Career progression can stall because remote workers are less visible to managers\n- The boundary between work and personal life becomes blurred, leading to longer hours\n- Remote work allows companies to recruit talent from a wider geographical area\n- Collaboration and spontaneous idea generation suffer without in-person interaction\n- Environmental benefits include reduced carbon emissions from commuting\n\nWrite your summary in no more than 200 words. You will receive up to 10 marks for content and 5 marks for quality of writing.",
    modelAnswer:
      "Remote working offers significant practical and economic benefits but raises concerns about wellbeing and professional development.\n\nEmployees benefit substantially from eliminating the daily commute, reclaiming over an hour each day that can be redirected towards productive work or personal life. Studies suggest that home-based workers accomplish nearly fifty per cent more on tasks requiring deep concentration, likely because they face fewer workplace interruptions. Employers also gain financially, saving thousands of pounds annually per employee on office space, utilities, and related overheads. Additionally, remote recruitment removes geographical barriers, enabling organisations to access a broader and more diverse talent pool. The environmental advantages are equally compelling, as fewer commuters mean reduced vehicle emissions.\n\nHowever, these benefits come at a cost. Workers frequently report feelings of isolation and loneliness, which can damage mental health over time. Without physical presence in the office, employees risk becoming invisible to decision-makers, potentially hindering promotion prospects. The absence of clear boundaries between professional and domestic spaces often results in extended working hours, ironically undermining the time saved by not commuting. Finally, the informal exchanges that fuel creative collaboration — corridor conversations, impromptu meetings — are difficult to replicate virtually.\n\nThe evidence suggests remote working is beneficial but requires careful management to mitigate its drawbacks.",
    markScheme:
      "Reading (10 marks): Accurate identification of key points from both sides. Writing (5 marks): Concise, fluent expression in own words. Band 5: All relevant points in well-organised, fluent prose. Band 3: Most points covered with some own words.",
