    question:
      'Your school is considering how to spend a £50,000 improvement budget. The headteacher has asked students to submit a formal report recommending how the money should be spent.\n\nWrite a report for the headteacher in which you:\n- identify two or three areas of the school that most need improvement\n- explain why these improvements would benefit students\n- suggest how the money should be divided between your recommendations\n- acknowledge any potential objections to your proposals\n\nWrite between 250-350 words. You will receive up to 15 marks for writing and 10 marks for reading.',
    modelAnswer:
      'REPORT: Recommended Allocation of the School Improvement Budget\n\nPrepared for: Mrs Henderson, Headteacher\nPrepared by: Year 11 Student Council Representative\nDate: March 2026\n\n1. Introduction\nThis report recommends how the £50,000 improvement budget should be allocated to maximise benefit for students. Following consultation with students across all year groups, three priority areas have been identified.\n\n2. Recommendations\n\n2.1 Library and Study Space (£20,000)\nThe school library has not been updated since 2015. The current stock is outdated, seating is insufficient during exam periods, and there are no dedicated quiet study areas. An investment of £20,000 would allow for new book purchases, the creation of individual study pods, and improved lighting. This would directly support academic achievement, particularly for students who lack quiet study space at home — a group that, according to school survey data, constitutes approximately 35% of the student body.\n\n2.2 Sports Facilities (£18,000)\nThe outdoor basketball courts are in poor condition, with uneven surfaces that present a safety concern. The gymnasium lacks adequate ventilation, which discourages use during warmer months. Resurfacing the courts (approximately £12,000) and installing ventilation in the gym (approximately £6,000) would improve both safety and participation in physical activity, contributing to student wellbeing.\n\n2.3 Mental Health and Wellbeing Room (£12,000)\nCurrently, students seeking support from the school counsellor must use a shared office that offers little privacy. A dedicated, appropriately furnished wellbeing room would provide a calm, confidential space. The investment would cover soundproofing, comfortable furniture, and resources. Given the increasing demand for mental health support in schools, this represents a timely and necessary provision.\n\n3. Potential Objections\nSome may argue that technology upgrades should take priority. However, the school\'s devices were updated two years ago and remain functional. The areas identified above represent more urgent needs.\n\n4. Conclusion\nThe proposed allocation prioritises academic support, physical safety, and mental wellbeing — three areas that collectively address the most pressing student concerns.',
